05209nam a22006615i 9780691261157DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912611577 a10.1515/97806912611572doi  a(DE-B1597)671766  a(OCoLC)1412008511  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHB172.5b.F79 2007 7aBUS0690302bisacsh04a330.1222/eng/202302161 aFrydman, Roman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImperfect Knowledge Economics :bExchange Rates and Risk /cRoman Frydman, Michael D. Goldberg. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (366 p.) :b35 line illus. 14 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tPART I. From Early Modern Economics to Imperfect Knowledge Economics -- t1 Recognizing the Limits of Economists’ Knowledge -- t2 A Tradition Interrupted -- t3 Flawed Foundations -- t4 Reconsidering Modern Economics -- t5 Imperfect Knowledge Economics of Supply and Demand -- tPART II. “Anomalies” in Contemporary Models of Currency Markets -- t6 The Overreach of Contemporary Models of Asset Markets -- t7 The “Puzzling” Behavior of Exchange Rates -- t8 “Anomalous” Returns on Foreign Exchange -- tPART III. Imperfect Knowledge Economics of Exchange Rates and Risk -- t9 Modeling Preferences in Asset Markets -- t10 Modeling Individual Forecasting Strategies and Their Revisions -- t11 Bulls and Bears in Equilibrium -- t12 IKE of the Premium on Foreign Exchange -- t13 The Forward Discount “Anomaly” -- t14 Imperfect Knowledge and Long Swings in the Exchange Rate -- t15 Exchange Rates and Macroeconomic Fundamentals -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPosing a major challenge to economic orthodoxy, Imperfect Knowledge Economics asserts that exact models of purposeful human behavior are beyond the reach of economic analysis. Roman Frydman and Michael Goldberg argue that the longstanding empirical failures of conventional economic models stem from their futile efforts to make exact predictions about the consequences of rational, self-interested behavior. Such predictions, based on mechanistic models of human behavior, disregard the importance of individual creativity and unforeseeable sociopolitical change. Scientific though these explanations may appear, they usually fail to predict how markets behave. And, the authors contend, recent behavioral models of the market are no less mechanistic than their conventional counterparts: they aim to generate exact predictions of ";irrational"; human behavior.Frydman and Goldberg offer a long-overdue response to the shortcomings of conventional economic models. Drawing attention to the inherent limits of economists' knowledge, they introduce a new approach to economic analysis: Imperfect Knowledge Economics (IKE). IKE rejects exact quantitative predictions of individual decisions and market outcomes in favor of mathematical models that generate only qualitative predictions of economic change. Using the foreign exchange market as a testing ground for IKE, this book sheds new light on exchange-rate and risk-premium movements, which have confounded conventional models for decades.Offering a fresh way to think about markets and representing a potential turning point in economics, Imperfect Knowledge Economics will be essential reading for economists, policymakers, and professional investors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEquilibrium (Economics). 0aForeign exchange. 0aMicroeconomics. 0aRational expectations (Economic theory). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh1 aGoldb